1
00:04:22,311 --> 00:04:24,732
I'm requesting--

2
00:04:24,807 --> 00:04:28,769
Captain, I'd like to request
that it be me who's the attorney--

3
00:04:28,840 --> 00:04:31,490
That it be myself who’s assigned.

4
00:04:31,559 --> 00:04:34,278
No, I'd like to request
that it be I who am assigned--

5
00:04:35,784 --> 00:04:37,857
'That it be I who am assigned'?

6
00:04:37,928 --> 00:04:41,126
That's good.
That's confidence-inspiring.

7
00:04:41,193 --> 00:04:43,047
Good grammar there.

8
00:04:43,113 --> 00:04:45,217
Captain, I'd like to request...

9
00:04:45,288 --> 00:04:48,638
that I be the attorney assigned.

10
00:04:50,826 --> 00:04:53,128
I'm Lieutenant Commander Galloway
here to see Captain West.

11
00:04:53,194 --> 00:04:55,049
Go right in, Commander.
They're expecting you.

12
00:04:55,114 --> 00:04:56,489
Thank you.

13
00:04:59,914 --> 00:05:01,769
-Jo, come on in.
- Thank you, sir.

14
00:05:02,858 --> 00:05:05,641
Captain West,
this is Lieutenant Commander Galloway.

15
00:05:05,706 --> 00:05:07,975
-Jo, you know Commander Lawrence.
- Yes, sir.

16
00:05:08,042 --> 00:05:10,116
Captain, I appreciate
you seeing me on such short notice.

17
00:05:10,187 --> 00:05:12,643
- Would you like to sit down?
- I'm fine, sir.

18
00:05:12,716 --> 00:05:15,083
- Have a seat.
- Okay.

19
00:05:15,147 --> 00:05:17,252
I understand we had some trouble
over the weekend down in Cuba?

20
00:05:17,323 --> 00:05:20,488
Yes, sir.
This past Friday, two Marines--

21
00:05:20,556 --> 00:05:24,352
a Lance Corporal Harold Dawson
and a Private Louden Downey--

22
00:05:24,428 --> 00:05:28,455
entered the barracks room of a P.F.C.
William Santiago and assaulted him.

23
00:05:28,525 --> 00:05:31,874
Santiago died at the base hospital
approximately an hour later.

24
00:05:31,949 --> 00:05:35,332
The N.I.S. Agent who took
Dawson and Downey's statements...

25
00:05:35,405 --> 00:05:37,609
maintains they were trying
to prevent Santiago...

26
00:05:37,678 --> 00:05:40,394
from naming Dawson
in a fence line shooting incident.

27
00:05:40,460 --> 00:05:44,073
They're scheduled to have a hearing
down in Cuba this afternoon at 1600.

28
00:05:44,142 --> 00:05:45,996
- What's the problem?
- Dawson and Downey...

29
00:05:46,062 --> 00:05:50,220
are both recruiting poster Marines,
and Santiago was known to be a screw-up.

30
00:05:50,287 --> 00:05:52,937
I was thinking it sounded an awful lot
like a Code Red.

31
00:05:53,710 --> 00:05:55,204
Christ.

32
00:05:55,278 --> 00:05:58,792
Sir, I'd like to have them moved
up to Washington and assigned counsel--

33
00:05:58,863 --> 00:06:01,066
someone who can really
look into this--

34
00:06:01,134 --> 00:06:03,404
someone who possesses
not only the legal skill...

35
00:06:03,471 --> 00:06:06,287
but a familiarity
with the inner workings of the military.

36
00:06:06,352 --> 00:06:08,741
In short, Captain,
I'd like to suggest that...

37
00:06:08,816 --> 00:06:10,704
I be the one who that--

38
00:06:10,769 --> 00:06:14,282
that it be me who is assigned
to represent them...

39
00:06:14,353 --> 00:06:15,727
myself.

40
00:06:17,712 --> 00:06:20,134
Commander Galloway, why don’t you
get yourself a cup of coffee?

41
00:06:20,209 --> 00:06:22,118
Thank you, sir. I'm fine.

42
00:06:22,193 --> 00:06:25,260
I'd like you to leave the room so
we can talk about you behind your back.

43
00:06:25,330 --> 00:06:27,184
Certainly, sir.

44
00:06:33,682 --> 00:06:36,616
I thought this Code Red shit
wasn't going on anymore.

45
00:06:36,690 --> 00:06:39,657
With the Marines at Gitmo, who knows
what the hell goes on down there?

46
00:06:39,729 --> 00:06:41,617
We better find out
before the rest of the world does.

47
00:06:41,683 --> 00:06:43,625
Damn thing could get messy.

48
00:06:43,699 --> 00:06:46,121
All right,
what about this Commander Galloway?

49
00:06:46,195 --> 00:06:49,196
She's been working a desk
in Internal Affairs...

50
00:06:49,268 --> 00:06:51,123
for a little over a year now.

51
00:06:51,188 --> 00:06:54,057
- Before that?
- Disposed of three cases in two years.

52
00:06:54,131 --> 00:06:56,848
Three cases in two years?
Who's she handling, the Rosenberg’s?

53
00:06:56,916 --> 00:06:59,337
- She's not cut out for litigation.
- She's a hell of a investigator.

54
00:06:59,412 --> 00:07:02,762
In Internal Affairs she can crawl up
a lawyer's ass with the best of them.

55
00:07:02,837 --> 00:07:06,514
- But when it comes to trial work--
- I know. All passion, no street smarts.

56
00:07:06,581 --> 00:07:08,435
Bring her back in.

57
00:07:18,486 --> 00:07:21,334
Commander, we're gonna have the
defendants moved up here in the morning.

58
00:07:21,398 --> 00:07:24,432
- Thank you, sir.
- Division will assign them counsel.

59
00:07:25,335 --> 00:07:29,644
-But not me.
-From what I get from your colleagues...

60
00:07:29,718 --> 00:07:31,955
you're much too valuable in your
present assignment to be wasted...

61
00:07:32,023 --> 00:07:34,031
in what I'm sure will boil down
to a five-minute plea bargain...

62
00:07:34,103 --> 00:07:35,957
and a week's worth of paperwork.

63
00:07:36,022 --> 00:07:38,063
Sir, I think there might be
more involved than that.

64
00:07:38,136 --> 00:07:39,510
Don't worry about it.

65
00:07:39,575 --> 00:07:42,358
I promise you Division will assign
the right man for the job.

66
00:07:42,776 --> 00:07:44,663
All right. Let's go.
Let's get two.

67
00:07:46,168 --> 00:07:48,274
- Sorry.
- Nothing to be sorry about, Sherby.

68
00:07:48,345 --> 00:07:50,450
You just look the ball
into your glove.

69
00:07:50,521 --> 00:07:51,895
Shooting two.

70
00:07:53,624 --> 00:07:55,512
- Sorry.
- You gotta trust me, Sherby.

71
00:07:55,576 --> 00:07:59,155
Keep your eyes open, your chances of
catching it increase by a factor often.

72
00:07:59,225 --> 00:08:01,014
- Kaffee.
- Let's try it again.

73
00:08:02,138 --> 00:08:04,048
Dave, you seem distraught.

74
00:08:04,122 --> 00:08:06,772
We were supposed to meet 15 minutes ago
about the McDermott case.

75
00:08:06,842 --> 00:08:09,427
You're stalling on this thing.
Now we either do it now...

76
00:08:09,497 --> 00:08:12,946
or, no kidding, Kaffee, I'm gonna
hang your boy from a fucking yardarm!

77
00:08:13,018 --> 00:08:16,815
Yardarm? Sherby, does the Navy
still hang people from yardarms?

78
00:08:16,891 --> 00:08:18,299
I don't think so.

79
00:08:18,364 --> 00:08:21,560
Dave, Sherby doesn't think the Navy
hangs people from yardarms anymore.

80
00:08:21,627 --> 00:08:24,857
I'm gonna charge him with possession
and being under the influence on duty.

81
00:08:24,924 --> 00:08:28,917
You plead guilty, I'll recommend 30 days
in the brig with loss frank and pay.

82
00:08:28,987 --> 00:08:31,834
It was oregano, Dave.
It was $10 worth of oregano.

83
00:08:31,899 --> 00:08:33,755
Yeah, well, your client thought
it was marijuana.

84
00:08:33,821 --> 00:08:36,439
My client's a moron.
That's not against the law.

85
00:08:36,508 --> 00:08:39,738
Kaffee, I got people to answer to
just like you do. I'm gonna charge him.

86
00:08:39,805 --> 00:08:41,943
With what,
possession of a condiment?

87
00:08:42,013 --> 00:08:44,468
- Kaffee.
- I tried to help you out of this...

88
00:08:44,540 --> 00:08:47,159
but if you ask for jail time,
I'm gonna file a motion to dismiss.

89
00:08:47,229 --> 00:08:49,018
- You won't get it.
- I will get it.

90
00:08:49,086 --> 00:08:50,940
And if the M.T.D. is denied,
I'll file a motion...

91
00:08:51,005 --> 00:08:53,723
seeking to obtain
an evidentiary ruling in advance.

92
00:08:53,789 --> 00:08:56,059
And after that, I'm gonna file
against pretrial confinement.

93
00:08:56,126 --> 00:08:58,548
And you're gonna spend the next three
months going blind on paperwork...

94
00:08:58,622 --> 00:09:02,103
because a signalman second-class bought
and smoked a dime bag of oregano.

95
00:09:02,175 --> 00:09:04,597
Let's go! Let's get two!

96
00:09:05,630 --> 00:09:07,964
B misdemeanor,
20 days in the brig.

97
00:09:08,031 --> 00:09:10,203
C misdemeanor,
15 days restricted duty.

98
00:09:11,616 --> 00:09:13,558
I don't know why
I'm agreeing to this.

99
00:09:13,632 --> 00:09:15,803
'Cause you have wisdom
beyond your years.

100
00:09:19,552 --> 00:09:21,145
Morning.

101
00:09:21,216 --> 00:09:22,842
Morning, Captain.

102
00:09:22,912 --> 00:09:24,374
How's the baby, Sam?

103
00:09:24,449 --> 00:09:27,515
I think she's getting ready
to say her first word any day now.

104
00:09:27,585 --> 00:09:29,111
How can you tell?

105
00:09:29,184 --> 00:09:32,666
She just looks
like she has something to say.

106
00:09:32,738 --> 00:09:35,225
Excuse me.
I'm sorry I'm late.

107
00:09:35,297 --> 00:09:37,207
It's all right, Danny.
I know you don't have a good excuse...

108
00:09:37,281 --> 00:09:39,257
so I won't force you
to come up with a bad one.

109
00:09:39,330 --> 00:09:42,144
- Thank you, sir.
- This first one's for you.

110
00:09:43,169 --> 00:09:45,438
Seems you're moving up
in the world.

111
00:09:45,505 --> 00:09:47,361
Been requested by Division.

112
00:09:48,226 --> 00:09:50,081
Requested to do what?

113
00:09:50,147 --> 00:09:52,416
Guantanamo Bay, Cuba.

114
00:09:52,483 --> 00:09:56,378
A Marine corporal named Dawson illegally
fires a round from his weapon...

115
00:09:56,451 --> 00:09:59,200
over the fence line
and into Cuban territory.

116
00:09:59,267 --> 00:10:01,089
- What's a fence line?
- Sam.

117
00:10:01,154 --> 00:10:05,181
A big wall separating the good guys
from the bad guys.

118
00:10:05,251 --> 00:10:08,383
- Teacher's pet.
- P.F.C. William Santiago...

119
00:10:08,452 --> 00:10:11,649
threatens to rat on Dawson
to Naval Investigative Service.

120
00:10:11,716 --> 00:10:13,658
Dawson and another member
of his squad...

121
00:10:13,732 --> 00:10:17,529
P.F.C. Louden Downey,
go into Santiago's room...

122
00:10:17,605 --> 00:10:20,867
tie him up,
stuff a rag down his throat...

123
00:10:20,933 --> 00:10:22,940
and an hour later, Santiago's dead.

124
00:10:23,013 --> 00:10:26,560
Attending physician says the rag
was treated with some kind of toxin.

125
00:10:26,630 --> 00:10:27,807
They poisoned it?

126
00:10:27,877 --> 00:10:30,692
- Not according to them.
- What did they say?

127
00:10:30,757 --> 00:10:33,278
Not much.
They're being flown up here tomorrow...

128
00:10:33,350 --> 00:10:36,666
and on Wednesday at 0600, you'll catch
a transport down to Cuba for the day...

129
00:10:36,742 --> 00:10:38,597
to find out what you can.

130
00:10:38,663 --> 00:10:42,208
Meantime, go and see
Lieutenant Commander Joanne Galloway...

131
00:10:43,687 --> 00:10:45,280
with Internal Affairs.

132
00:10:45,351 --> 00:10:46,814
Any questions?

133
00:10:46,888 --> 00:10:50,749
Uh, the flight to Cuba--
Was that 0600 in the morning, sir?

134
00:10:51,847 --> 00:10:54,150
Seems important to Division
that this one be handled by the book.

135
00:10:54,216 --> 00:10:58,078
So I'm assigning co-counsel.
Any volunteers?

136
00:11:00,648 --> 00:11:02,558
I got a stack of papers on my desk
about a mile high.

137
00:11:02,633 --> 00:11:04,488
- Work with Kaffee on this.
- Doing what?

138
00:11:04,553 --> 00:11:06,692
Kaffee will have this done
in about four days.

139
00:11:06,761 --> 00:11:09,893
Doing various administrative things.

140
00:11:09,962 --> 00:11:11,816
Backup, whatever.

141
00:11:11,882 --> 00:11:14,337
In other words, I have
no responsibilities here whatsoever.

142
00:11:14,409 --> 00:11:15,838
Right.

143
00:11:15,914 --> 00:11:17,921
My kind of case.

144
00:11:18,954 --> 00:11:20,863
Right.

145
00:11:20,937 --> 00:11:23,327
Okay, but I've got to have
that report by Wednesday.

146
00:11:29,451 --> 00:11:32,069
- Hi.
- Hold on. Hi.

147
00:11:32,139 --> 00:11:34,376
Daniel Kaffee.
I was told to me with, uh--

148
00:11:41,964 --> 00:11:44,331
Lieutenant Commander Galloway.

149
00:11:46,477 --> 00:11:47,687
About a briefing?

150
00:11:47,757 --> 00:11:49,611
I'll call you back.

151
00:11:52,236 --> 00:11:54,092
You're the attorney Division assigned?

152
00:11:54,957 --> 00:11:56,811
I'm lead counsel.
This is Sam Weinberg.

153
00:11:56,876 --> 00:11:58,950
I have no responsibilities here
whatsoever.

154
00:11:59,022 --> 00:12:01,095
Come in, please. Have a seat.

155
00:12:11,118 --> 00:12:13,190
Lieutenant, how long
have you been in the Navy?

156
00:12:14,797 --> 00:12:16,653
Going on nine months now.

157
00:12:16,718 --> 00:12:19,207
And how long have you been
out of law school?

158
00:12:20,367 --> 00:12:21,774
A little over a year.

159
00:12:21,839 --> 00:12:23,847
I see.

160
00:12:24,559 --> 00:12:26,086
Have I done something wrong?

161
00:12:26,160 --> 00:12:28,713
It’s just that when I petition Division
to have counsel assigned...

162
00:12:28,784 --> 00:12:30,694
I was hoping I'd be taken seriously.

163
00:12:30,768 --> 00:12:33,353
No offense taken,
in case you were wondering.

164
00:12:33,424 --> 00:12:35,212
Commander,
Lieutenant Kaffee is generally...

165
00:12:35,279 --> 00:12:37,549
considered the best litigator
in our office.

166
00:12:37,616 --> 00:12:40,716
He's successfully plea-bargained
44 cases in nine months.

167
00:12:40,785 --> 00:12:42,694
One more,
I get a set of steak knives.

168
00:12:42,769 --> 00:12:44,492
Have you ever been in a courtroom?

169
00:12:44,560 --> 00:12:46,982
I once had
my driver's license suspended.

170
00:12:47,057 --> 00:12:48,944
Commander, from what I understand,
if this thing goes to court...

171
00:12:49,009 --> 00:12:51,081
they won’t need a lawyer,
they'll need a priest.

172
00:12:51,697 --> 00:12:53,552
No, they'll need a lawyer.

173
00:12:54,577 --> 00:12:56,553
Dawson's family's been contacted.

174
00:12:56,627 --> 00:13:00,009
Downey's closest living relative
is Ginny Miller, his aunt.

175
00:13:00,082 --> 00:13:02,865
She hasn't been contacted yet.
Would you like me to take care of that?

176
00:13:02,931 --> 00:13:04,360
If you feel like it.

177
00:13:06,067 --> 00:13:07,922
One of the people
you'll be seeing down there...

178
00:13:07,987 --> 00:13:09,962
is the barracks C.O.,
Colonel Nathan Jessup.

179
00:13:10,035 --> 00:13:12,074
I assume you’ve heard of him.

180
00:13:12,147 --> 00:13:13,522
Who hasn't?

181
00:13:14,547 --> 00:13:17,036
He's been in the papers lately.
He's expected to be appointed...

182
00:13:17,108 --> 00:13:19,825
director of operations
of National Security Council.

183
00:13:19,892 --> 00:13:21,135
- Really?
- These are the letters...

184
00:13:21,204 --> 00:13:23,408
that Santiago wrote
in his eight months at Gitmo.

185
00:13:23,476 --> 00:13:25,843
- That's Guantanamo Bay.
- I knew that one.

186
00:13:25,908 --> 00:13:29,290
He wrote to the fleet commander
to the commandant of the Marine Corps.

187
00:13:29,364 --> 00:13:32,181
Even his senator. He wanted
to be transferred off the base.

188
00:13:32,246 --> 00:13:34,100
No one was listening.
Are you with me?

189
00:13:34,166 --> 00:13:35,988
Yeah.

190
00:13:37,173 --> 00:13:39,083
Finally, he wrote
to the Naval Investigative Service...

191
00:13:39,158 --> 00:13:42,060
where he offered information about
Corporal Dawson's fence line shooting...

192
00:13:42,134 --> 00:13:44,654
in exchange for a transfer.

193
00:13:44,726 --> 00:13:47,247
Right. Is that all?

194
00:13:47,319 --> 00:13:49,173
Lieutenant,
this letter makes it look like...

195
00:13:49,238 --> 00:13:51,573
your client had a motive
to kill Santiago.

196
00:13:51,639 --> 00:13:54,771
Got you.
And Santiago is who?

197
00:13:54,840 --> 00:13:56,366
The victim.

198
00:13:56,439 --> 00:13:58,959
Write that down.
Am I correct to assume these letters...

199
00:13:59,031 --> 00:14:01,814
don't paint a flattering picture
of Marine Corps life at Guantanamo Bay?

200
00:14:01,879 --> 00:14:03,286
- Yes, among--
- Am I further right in assuming...

201
00:14:03,351 --> 00:14:07,028
investigation of this incident might
embarrass the Security Council guy?

202
00:14:07,095 --> 00:14:09,005
- Colonel Jessup.
- Twelve years.

203
00:14:10,041 --> 00:14:10,935
Sorry?

204
00:14:11,001 --> 00:14:13,106
I'll get them to drop the conspiracy
and conduct unbecoming.

205
00:14:13,177 --> 00:14:14,868
Twelve years.

206
00:14:14,937 --> 00:14:18,417
You haven't talked to a witness
or looked at a piece of paper.

207
00:14:18,489 --> 00:14:20,464
Pretty impressive, huh?

208
00:14:20,537 --> 00:14:22,162
You're gonna have
to go deeper than that.

209
00:14:22,234 --> 00:14:24,884
Do you have some sort of jurisdiction
here that I should know about?

210
00:14:24,953 --> 00:14:27,637
My job is to make sure
that you do your job.

211
00:14:27,705 --> 00:14:29,593
I'm special counsel
for Internal Affairs...

212
00:14:29,659 --> 00:14:32,888
so my jurisdiction’s pretty much
in your face.

213
00:14:34,970 --> 00:14:37,905
Read the letters. I'll expect
your report when you return from Cuba.

214
00:14:37,979 --> 00:14:40,532
- Sure.
- You're dismissed.

215
00:14:42,714 --> 00:14:44,951
I always forget that part.

216
00:14:46,652 --> 00:14:49,302
He's a little preoccupied.

217
00:14:49,371 --> 00:14:52,405
Team's playing Bethesda Medical
next week.

218
00:14:52,476 --> 00:14:54,331
Tell your friend
not to get cute down there.

219
00:14:54,396 --> 00:14:56,632
The Marines in Guantanamo
are fanatical.

220
00:14:56,699 --> 00:14:57,943
About what?

221
00:14:58,652 --> 00:15:00,246
About being Marines.

222
00:15:00,317 --> 00:15:01,299
Dear sir...

223
00:15:01,372 --> 00:15:04,023
my name is P.F. C. William T. Santiago.

224
00:15:04,092 --> 00:15:06,329
I'm a Marine stationed
at Marine barracks...

225
00:15:06,397 --> 00:15:09,464
Rifle Security Company Windward,
Second Platoon Bravo.

226
00:15:09,533 --> 00:15:13,177
I'm writing to inform you of my problems
with my unit here in Cuba...

227
00:15:13,245 --> 00:15:14,806
and to ask for your help.

228
00:15:14,878 --> 00:15:18,074
I've fallen out on runs before
for several reasons...

229
00:15:18,142 --> 00:15:20,029
such as feeling dizzy or nauseated.

230
00:15:20,093 --> 00:15:23,673
Buton May 18, I'd fallen back
about20 or30yards...

231
00:15:23,743 --> 00:15:26,164
going down a rocky unstable hill.

232
00:15:26,239 --> 00:15:29,086
My sergeant grabbed me
and pushed me down the hill.

233
00:15:29,150 --> 00:15:32,893
Then Isawall black, and the last thing
I remembered was hitting the deck.

234
00:15:32,959 --> 00:15:36,188
I was brought to the hospital where
I was told I just had heat exhaustion.

235
00:15:36,255 --> 00:15:37,816
I ask you to help me.

236
00:15:37,887 --> 00:15:41,203
Please, sir. I just need
to be transferred out of R.S. C.

237
00:15:41,279 --> 00:15:43,997
Sincerely,
P.F. C. William T. Santiago...

238
00:15:44,064 --> 00:15:45,591
U.S. Marine Corps.

239
00:15:45,664 --> 00:15:48,479
P.S. In exchange for my transfer
off the base...

240
00:15:48,544 --> 00:15:50,453
I'm willing to provide you
with information about--

241
00:15:50,528 --> 00:15:54,620
'The illegal fence line shooting
that occurred the night of August 2.'

242
00:15:55,520 --> 00:15:59,711
Who the fuck
is P.F.C. William T. Santiago?

243
00:15:59,777 --> 00:16:02,745
Private Santiago is a member
of Second Platoon Bravo, sir.

244
00:16:02,818 --> 00:16:06,845
Yeah. Well, apparently he's not
very happy down here in Shangri-la...

245
00:16:06,915 --> 00:16:09,664
because he's written letters
to everybody but Santa Claus...

246
00:16:09,730 --> 00:16:11,770
asking for a transfer.

247
00:16:11,842 --> 00:16:14,657
And now he's telling tales
about a fence line shooting.

248
00:16:15,682 --> 00:16:17,209
Matthew?

249
00:16:17,283 --> 00:16:19,739
I'm appalled, sir.

250
00:16:20,515 --> 00:16:22,850
You're appalled.

251
00:16:23,876 --> 00:16:27,258
This kid broke the chain of command
and ratted on a member of his unit...

252
00:16:27,332 --> 00:16:30,016
to say nothing of the fact
that he is a U.S. Marine...

253
00:16:30,084 --> 00:16:32,702
and it would appear he can't run
from here to there...

254
00:16:32,772 --> 00:16:35,422
without collapsing
from heat exhaustion.

255
00:16:35,491 --> 00:16:38,624
What the fuck is going on
in Bravo Company, Matthew?

256
00:16:38,693 --> 00:16:41,595
Colonel, I think it would be better
to hold this discussion in private.

257
00:16:41,669 --> 00:16:45,630
That won't be necessary, Colonel.
I can handle the situation, sir.

258
00:16:45,701 --> 00:16:49,279
The same way you handled Curtis Bell?
Don't interrupt me, Lieutenant!

259
00:16:49,349 --> 00:16:52,732
- I'm still your superior officer.
- And I'm yours, Matthew.

260
00:16:54,822 --> 00:16:57,757
I want to know
what we're going to do about this.

261
00:16:57,830 --> 00:17:00,645
I think Santiago should be transferred
off the base immediately.

262
00:17:00,711 --> 00:17:02,271
He's that bad, huh?

263
00:17:02,343 --> 00:17:04,382
Not only that. But word
of this letter is bound to get out.

264
00:17:04,454 --> 00:17:06,310
He's gonna get his ass whipped.

265
00:17:06,375 --> 00:17:10,237
Hmm. Transfer Santiago.

266
00:17:10,311 --> 00:17:13,694
Yes. I'm sure you’re right.

267
00:17:13,768 --> 00:17:16,157
I'm sure that's the thing to do.

268
00:17:17,800 --> 00:17:21,543
Wait. I've got a better idea.

269
00:17:21,609 --> 00:17:24,424
Let's transfer the whole squad
off the base.

270
00:17:24,489 --> 00:17:27,456
Let's-- On second thought, Windward--

271
00:17:27,529 --> 00:17:31,588
Let's transfer the whole
Windward Division off the base.

272
00:17:31,657 --> 00:17:35,138
John, go on out there
and get those boys down off the fence.

273
00:17:35,210 --> 00:17:37,599
They're packing their bags. Tom.

274
00:17:38,826 --> 00:17:41,127
- Sir.
- Get me the president on the phone.

275
00:17:41,194 --> 00:17:44,162
We're surrendering
our position in Cuba.

276
00:17:44,234 --> 00:17:46,568
- Yes, sir.
- Wait a minute, Tom.

277
00:17:46,634 --> 00:17:48,488
Don't get the president just yet.

278
00:17:48,554 --> 00:17:52,034
Maybe we should
consider this for a second.

279
00:17:52,106 --> 00:17:54,278
- Dismissed, Tom.
- Yes, sir.

280
00:17:55,339 --> 00:17:59,049
Maybe-- and I'm just
spit-balling here--

281
00:17:59,115 --> 00:18:03,937
Maybe we have a responsibility
as officers to train Santiago.

282
00:18:04,012 --> 00:18:08,006
Maybe we as officers
have a responsibility to this country...

283
00:18:08,076 --> 00:18:11,239
to see that the men and women
charged with its security...

284
00:18:11,307 --> 00:18:13,284
are trained professionals.

285
00:18:13,358 --> 00:18:17,132
Yes, I'm certain
that I read that somewhere once.

286
00:18:17,197 --> 00:18:19,685
And now I'm thinking,
Colonel Markinson...

287
00:18:19,757 --> 00:18:23,914
that your suggestion
of transferring Santiago...

288
00:18:23,981 --> 00:18:27,079
while expeditious
and certainly painless...

289
00:18:27,149 --> 00:18:29,539
might not be,
in a manner of speaking...

290
00:18:29,614 --> 00:18:32,397
the American way.

291
00:18:32,463 --> 00:18:35,146
Santiago stays where he is.

292
00:18:36,783 --> 00:18:39,019
We're gonna train the lad.

293
00:18:39,086 --> 00:18:41,901
John, you're in charge.

294
00:18:41,966 --> 00:18:45,000
Santiago doesn't make 4-6-4-6...

295
00:18:45,071 --> 00:18:48,585
on his next proficiency
and conduct report...

296
00:18:48,656 --> 00:18:50,893
I'm going to blame you.

297
00:18:50,960 --> 00:18:53,480
- Then I'm going to kill you.
- Yes, sir.

298
00:18:53,552 --> 00:18:56,040
I think that's a mistake, Colonel.

299
00:18:57,392 --> 00:19:01,353
Matthew, I think I will
have that word in private with you now.

300
00:19:01,424 --> 00:19:05,220
John, that's all. Why don't we meet
at the 'O' club and have lunch...

301
00:19:05,296 --> 00:19:07,786
and we'll talk about the training
of young William?

302
00:19:07,858 --> 00:19:10,476
I'd be delighted to hear any
suggestions that you might have, sir.

303
00:19:10,546 --> 00:19:12,433
- Dismissed.
- Yes, sir.

304
00:19:16,050 --> 00:19:19,116
Matthew, sit down. Please.

305
00:19:24,082 --> 00:19:26,571
What do you think of Kendrick?

306
00:19:26,642 --> 00:19:28,399
My opinion of him has nothing to do--

307
00:19:28,467 --> 00:19:31,500
I think he's pretty much
of a weasel myself...

308
00:19:31,571 --> 00:19:33,481
but he's an awfully good officer.

309
00:19:33,555 --> 00:19:37,810
And in the end, we see eye-to-eye on
the best way to run a Marine Corps unit.

310
00:19:37,876 --> 00:19:41,258
We're in the business
of saving lives, Matthew.

311
00:19:41,332 --> 00:19:44,879
That is a responsibility
that we have to take pretty seriously.

312
00:19:44,949 --> 00:19:49,105
And I believe that taking a Marine
who is not quite up to the job...

313
00:19:49,172 --> 00:19:51,540
and shipping him off
to another assignment...

314
00:19:51,605 --> 00:19:53,514
puts lives in danger.

315
00:19:54,261 --> 00:19:56,432
Sit down, Matthew.

316
00:20:05,559 --> 00:20:07,533
We go back a while.

317
00:20:07,607 --> 00:20:10,955
We went to the Academy together.
We were commissioned together.

318
00:20:11,030 --> 00:20:13,398
We did our tours in Vietnam together.

319
00:20:13,463 --> 00:20:15,732
But I've been promoted
up through the chain...

320
00:20:15,798 --> 00:20:18,580
with greater speed and success
than you have.

321
00:20:18,646 --> 00:20:21,494
Now, if that’s a source of tension...

322
00:20:21,559 --> 00:20:23,447
or embarrassment for you...

323
00:20:23,512 --> 00:20:25,203
I don't give a shit.

324
00:20:25,272 --> 00:20:30,258
We're in the business of saving lives,
Lieutenant Colonel Markinson.

325
00:20:30,328 --> 00:20:34,256
Don't ever question my orders
in front of another officer.

326
00:20:53,434 --> 00:20:54,841
All the paperwork's in order.

327
00:20:55,866 --> 00:20:57,721
- Step over there.
- Yes, sir.

328
00:21:02,203 --> 00:21:04,854
Hal, is this Washington, D.C.?

329
00:21:04,923 --> 00:21:06,483
All right. Let's move.

330
00:21:06,555 --> 00:21:07,929
Yes, sir.

331
00:21:14,223 --> 00:21:17,038
- Got all of that one.
- Excuse me.

332
00:21:17,103 --> 00:21:20,552
I wanted to talk to you about
Corporal Dawson and Private Downey.

333
00:21:20,625 --> 00:21:23,113
- Say again?
- Dawson and Downey.

334
00:21:24,336 --> 00:21:26,278
Those names sound like
they should mean something to me--

335
00:21:26,352 --> 00:21:29,036
Dawson, Downey--your clients.

336
00:21:29,105 --> 00:21:32,269
The Cuba thing. Yes!
Dawson and Downey. Right.

337
00:21:35,345 --> 00:21:37,320
I've done something wrong again,
haven't I?

338
00:21:37,394 --> 00:21:39,303
I was just wondering
why two guys have been locked up...

339
00:21:39,378 --> 00:21:42,030
since this morning while their lawyer's
outside hitting a ball.

340
00:21:43,954 --> 00:21:45,580
We need the practice.

341
00:21:45,650 --> 00:21:47,176
That wasn't funny.

342
00:21:47,890 --> 00:21:49,200
It was a little funny.

343
00:21:49,267 --> 00:21:52,431
Would you be very insulted
if I recommended to your supervisor...

344
00:21:52,499 --> 00:21:54,353
that he assign different counsel?

345
00:21:54,418 --> 00:21:57,715
- Why?
- I don't think you’re fit to handle it.

346
00:21:57,780 --> 00:22:01,391
You don't even know me.
Ordinarily, it takes someone hours...

347
00:22:01,460 --> 00:22:03,981
to discover I'm not fit
to handle a defense.

348
00:22:05,653 --> 00:22:08,881
Oh, come on.
That was damn funny.

349
00:22:11,765 --> 00:22:12,877
You're wrong.

350
00:22:13,909 --> 00:22:15,818
I do know you.

351
00:22:15,893 --> 00:22:19,571
Daniel Alistair Kaffee,
born June 8, 1964...

352
00:22:19,638 --> 00:22:21,492
at Boston Mercy Hospital.

353
00:22:21,558 --> 00:22:22,834
Your father's Lionel Kaffee...

354
00:22:22,901 --> 00:22:26,251
former Navy judge advocate and
attorney general of the United States.

355
00:22:26,326 --> 00:22:27,820
Died 1985.

356
00:22:27,893 --> 00:22:30,511
You went to Harvard law.
Then you joined the Navy...

357
00:22:30,581 --> 00:22:33,233
probably because that's
what your father wanted you to do.

358
00:22:33,302 --> 00:22:36,499
And now you're just treading water
for three years in the JAG Corps.

359
00:22:36,567 --> 00:22:39,916
Just laying low till
you can get out and get a real job.

360
00:22:39,991 --> 00:22:43,406
If that’s the situation, that's fine.
I won't tell anyone.

361
00:22:43,479 --> 00:22:45,683
But it's my feeling that
if this case is handled in the same...

362
00:22:45,751 --> 00:22:48,500
fast-food, slick-ass,
Persian bazaar manner...

363
00:22:48,566 --> 00:22:50,422
with which you seem
to handle everything else...

364
00:22:50,488 --> 00:22:52,081
then something's gonna get missed.

365
00:22:52,152 --> 00:22:54,705
And I wouldn't be doing my job
if allowed Dawson and Downey...

366
00:22:54,776 --> 00:22:57,231
to spend any more time in prison
than absolutely necessary...

367
00:22:57,304 --> 00:23:00,271
because their attorney had predetermined
the path of least resistance.

368
00:23:02,936 --> 00:23:04,311
Wow.

369
00:23:05,401 --> 00:23:07,767
I'm sexually aroused, Commander.

370
00:23:08,441 --> 00:23:10,613
I don't think
your clients murdered anyone.

371
00:23:10,682 --> 00:23:11,992
What are you basing this on?

372
00:23:12,058 --> 00:23:13,781
There was no intent.

373
00:23:13,850 --> 00:23:16,567
The doctor's report says
Santiago died of asphyxiation...

374
00:23:16,634 --> 00:23:18,489
brought on by acute lactic acidosis...

375
00:23:18,555 --> 00:23:22,231
and that the nature of the acidosis
strongly suggests poison.

376
00:23:22,298 --> 00:23:24,949
I don't know what any of that means,
but it sounds pretty bad.

377
00:23:25,018 --> 00:23:26,874
Santiago died at 1:00 a.m.

378
00:23:26,939 --> 00:23:29,623
At 3:00, the doctor wasn’t able
to determine the cause of death.

379
00:23:29,691 --> 00:23:31,829
Two hours later,
he said it was poison.

380
00:23:31,899 --> 00:23:34,322
Oh, now I see what you’re saying.

381
00:23:34,396 --> 00:23:37,559
It had to be Professor Plum
in the library with a candlestick.

382
00:23:37,627 --> 00:23:39,994
- I'm gonna talk to your supervisor.
- Okay.

383
00:23:40,059 --> 00:23:42,132
Go straight up Pennsylvania Avenue.

384
00:23:42,204 --> 00:23:44,593
It's the big white house
with the pillars in front.

385
00:23:44,668 --> 00:23:47,734
- Thank you.
- I don't think you’ll have much luck.

386
00:23:47,804 --> 00:23:49,180
I was assigned by Division.

387
00:23:49,245 --> 00:23:52,179
Somebody over there thinks
I'm a pretty good lawyer.

388
00:23:52,253 --> 00:23:55,602
So while I appreciate your interest
and admire your enthusiasm...

389
00:23:55,677 --> 00:23:58,044
I think I can handle things myself.

390
00:23:58,109 --> 00:24:00,116
You know what a Code Red is?

391
00:24:03,838 --> 00:24:05,879
What a pity.

392
00:24:15,678 --> 00:24:18,046
- Morning, sir.
- Morning.

393
00:24:18,943 --> 00:24:20,536
Officer on deck!

394
00:24:20,607 --> 00:24:22,679
Sir, Lance Corporal
Harold W. Dawson, sir!

395
00:24:22,750 --> 00:24:24,856
Rifle Security Company Windward,
Second Platoon Bravo.

396
00:24:24,927 --> 00:24:28,059
Someone hasn't been working
and playing well with others, Harold.

397
00:24:28,128 --> 00:24:29,983
Sir, yes, sir!

398
00:24:31,680 --> 00:24:33,917
Sir, P.F.C. Louden Downey, sir!

399
00:24:35,361 --> 00:24:37,848
I'm Daniel Kaffee.
This is Sam Weinberg.

400
00:24:37,920 --> 00:24:39,032
Sit down.

401
00:24:46,049 --> 00:24:48,733
- This your signature?
- Yes, sir.

402
00:24:48,802 --> 00:24:50,525
You don't have to call me 'sir.'
Is this your signature?

403
00:24:50,594 --> 00:24:51,739
Sir, yes, sir.

404
00:24:51,809 --> 00:24:54,559
You certainly don't need
to do it twice in one sentence.

405
00:24:54,626 --> 00:24:58,074
- What's a Code Red?
- It is a disciplinary engagement.

406
00:24:58,146 --> 00:24:59,520
What's that mean?

407
00:24:59,586 --> 00:25:03,297
A Marine falls out of line, it's up to
the men in his unit to get him on track.

408
00:25:03,364 --> 00:25:06,713
- What's a garden variety Code Red?
- Sir?

409
00:25:06,787 --> 00:25:10,563
Harold, you say, 'sir,' and
I turn around and look for my father.

410
00:25:10,628 --> 00:25:13,083
Danny, Daniel, Kaffee.

411
00:25:13,156 --> 00:25:16,090
Garden variety. Typical.
What's basic Code Red?

412
00:25:16,163 --> 00:25:18,684
Sir, a Marine refuses to bathe
on a regular basis...

413
00:25:18,756 --> 00:25:21,244
the men in his squad
will give him a G.I. shower.

414
00:25:21,316 --> 00:25:22,527
What's that?

415
00:25:22,597 --> 00:25:25,018
Scrub brushes,
Brillo pads, steel wool.

416
00:25:25,094 --> 00:25:26,370
Beautiful.

417
00:25:26,437 --> 00:25:28,858
Was the attack on Santiago
a Code Red?

418
00:25:28,933 --> 00:25:30,559
Yes, sir.

419
00:25:35,589 --> 00:25:38,623
Does he ever talk?

420
00:25:38,693 --> 00:25:41,858
Sir, P.F.C. Downey will answer
any direct questions you ask him.

421
00:25:41,926 --> 00:25:43,420
Swell.

422
00:25:44,966 --> 00:25:47,617
Private Downey, the rag
you stuffed in Santiago's mouth--

423
00:25:47,686 --> 00:25:49,541
- Was there poison on it?
- No, sir.

424
00:25:49,606 --> 00:25:51,995
Silver polish,
turpentine, antifreeze?

425
00:25:52,071 --> 00:25:54,340
No, sir. We were just
gonna shave his head, sir.

426
00:25:54,406 --> 00:25:57,091
When all of the sudden--

427
00:25:57,160 --> 00:25:59,494
We saw blood dripping
down his mouth...

428
00:25:59,560 --> 00:26:03,587
and we pulled the tape off and
there was blood all down his face, sir.

429
00:26:03,656 --> 00:26:06,787
That's when Lance Corporal Dawson
called the ambulance.

430
00:26:06,856 --> 00:26:08,481
Did anyone see you call
the ambulance?

431
00:26:10,409 --> 00:26:11,521
No, sir.

432
00:26:13,928 --> 00:26:15,587
Were you there
when the ambulance got there?

433
00:26:15,657 --> 00:26:17,927
Yes, sir. That's when
we were taken under arrest.

434
00:26:17,994 --> 00:26:22,598
The night of August 2, did you fire
a shot across the fence line into Cuba?

435
00:26:24,457 --> 00:26:25,832
- Yes, sir.
- Why?

436
00:26:25,898 --> 00:26:28,581
- My mirror engaged, sir.
- His mirror?

437
00:26:28,650 --> 00:26:32,360
Every American sentry post has
a Cuban counterpart, called 'mirrors.'

438
00:26:32,426 --> 00:26:35,743
Lance Corporal's claiming that
his mirror was about to fire at him.

439
00:26:35,819 --> 00:26:38,186
Santiago's letter to the N.I.S....

440
00:26:38,251 --> 00:26:40,619
said you fired illegally.

441
00:26:40,684 --> 00:26:44,458
He's saying that the guy, the mirror--

442
00:26:44,523 --> 00:26:46,050
He never made a move.

443
00:26:52,235 --> 00:26:54,091
You see what I'm getting at?

444
00:26:55,117 --> 00:26:58,215
If Santiago didn't have anything on you,
then why did you give him a Code Red?

445
00:26:58,284 --> 00:27:00,389
'Cause he broke
the chain of command, sir.

446
00:27:00,460 --> 00:27:03,308
- He what?
- He went outside of his unit, sir.

447
00:27:03,373 --> 00:27:05,675
If he had a problem,
he should have spoken to me, sir.

448
00:27:05,741 --> 00:27:08,643
- Then his sergeant, then commander--
- Yeah. All right.

449
00:27:08,717 --> 00:27:11,271
Did you assault Santiago
with the intent of killing him?

450
00:27:11,342 --> 00:27:12,935
- No, sir.
- What was your intent?

451
00:27:13,006 --> 00:27:15,657
- To train him, sir.
- Train him to do what?

452
00:27:15,726 --> 00:27:20,069
Train him to think of his unit
before himself-- to respect the code.

453
00:27:20,143 --> 00:27:21,866
What's the code?

454
00:27:21,934 --> 00:27:23,821
Unit, Corps, God, Country.

455
00:27:23,886 --> 00:27:25,097
I beg your pardon?

456
00:27:25,166 --> 00:27:30,317
Unit, Corps, God, Country, sir.

457
00:27:45,552 --> 00:27:48,335
The government
of the United States...

458
00:27:48,401 --> 00:27:51,085
wants to charge you two
with murder...

459
00:27:51,153 --> 00:27:53,062
and you want me
to go to the prosecutor...

460
00:27:53,137 --> 00:27:56,553
with ' Unit, Corps, God, Country'?

461
00:27:56,626 --> 00:27:58,535
That's our code, sir.

462
00:28:02,386 --> 00:28:04,142
It's your code.

463
00:28:04,210 --> 00:28:06,665
We'll be back.

464
00:28:06,738 --> 00:28:10,449
You guys need anything-- books,
papers, cigarettes, ham sandwich?

465
00:28:10,515 --> 00:28:12,719
Sir, no, thank you, sir.

466
00:28:12,787 --> 00:28:16,431
Harold, I think there's a concept
you better start warming up to.

467
00:28:16,499 --> 00:28:17,709
Sir?

468
00:28:17,779 --> 00:28:20,267
I'm the only friend you've got.

469
00:28:34,804 --> 00:28:36,014
Smiling Jack Ross.

470
00:28:36,084 --> 00:28:38,223
- Welcome to the big time.
- You think so?

471
00:28:38,292 --> 00:28:42,002
Let's hope, for Dawson and Downey, you
practice law better than play softball.

472
00:28:42,068 --> 00:28:45,452
Unfortunately for those two, I don't
do anything better than play softball.

473
00:28:45,525 --> 00:28:46,988
- I'm out of here, Janelle.
- Bye.

474
00:28:47,063 --> 00:28:49,266
- See you when I get back from Cuba.
- Say hi to Castro for me.

475
00:28:49,334 --> 00:28:51,538
Will do.
What are we looking at?

476
00:28:51,606 --> 00:28:54,640
They plead guilty, we drop
the conspiracy and conduct unbecoming.

477
00:28:54,710 --> 00:28:56,881
- Twenty years. They're home in half.
